Prologue
"Please!," pleaded Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King looked down from his throne at his wife, with his royal advisor beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He frowned at the thought.
The little girl resembled her mother greatly: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue strands. The Ice King believed that having a daughter would make him appear weak. After all, he had only sons until now.
Your only options are to kill your child or to send her back into nature. That is her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did this.
Frostwell had not always been a single kingdom. It had been split in two, North and South. In the north, the non-magical realm. In the south, a kingdom filled with fantastic representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two realms had torn themselves apart in an endless war, until the South offered a ceasefire.
Frostwell was cornered, and their royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their sole princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would ally with the North to form one united kingdom. The North agreed, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"Your highness, for my child's life, do with me as you will, imprison me, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his wife with disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he might pity her. The woman with whom he had lived for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Very well, the child can live in the palace," he began, eliciting a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen shared a horrified glance. She lowered her gaze gently. "Yes Your Highness," she said, bowing.
The Ice King ordered his royal advisor to take the child to one of the vacant chambers in Eirwen's quarters. Once that was done, he ordered the guards to bring Eirwen to the execution site, where all the villagers could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the villagers cried out in indignation at seeing their gentle queen about to be killed. Some people wept, others screamed and tried to attack the guards, while others wondered what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made her entrance. The user of fire. Queen Eirwen was to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruelest punishment in Frostwell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the user of fire incinerated the gallows, and a single tear rolled down the ex-queen's cheek.
"Survive, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds emanating from the farthest room to the left in the south wing of the still frozen palace. Servants passing by always wondered what was in that room, frightened of what might be inside. Rumors danced through the corridors. It was thought that the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be released.
"They could not be more wrong," thought Ivory as she walked towards the south wing, while the servants went back and forth whispering to each other. They have no idea what's in that room.
Certainly, these rumors applied to iel as well, since iel was the only person allowed to enter the room.
Toc Toc. "Miss Kari, are you there?"
Iel wondered if she would be invited to enter, unlike the other times when iel had asked. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at her shoulder, but once she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock came from inside, which seemed to mean she was there, but then again, where else could she be?
"Can I come in?"
A single knock echoed from inside. It seemed to imply yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold and also because of the sound. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a supposedly empty room, even though iel had entered this room many times over the years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, opening the door slowly. The scene inside the room was unusual according to normal standards, but not unexpected. Papers were scattered everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and numerous ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and very little light. It was also colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have descended upon the interior.
The girl huddled on her bed, wrapped in her blanket, reading one of her notebook pages. A small lantern illuminated the space.
"Which notebook are you reading from?" asked Ivory, sitting next to Kari on her bed.
